docs.abstract: While President Trump reassured business leaders that he wanted trade to continue, Beijing extended its economic reach to Latin America and the Arctic.
docs.snippet: While President Trump reassured business leaders that he wanted trade to continue, Beijing extended its economic reach to Latin America and the Arctic.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — President Trump used the World Economic Forum meeting to woo investors and business leaders by reassuring them that “America first does not mean America alone.” But it was clear in Davos, Switzerland, this past week that geopolitical momentum lay with Beijing, not Washington.

headline.main: At Davos, the Real Star May Have Been China, Not Trump
headline.print_headline: At Davos, It’s China That’s the Belle of the Ball

docs.abstract: Beijing is pushing companies to sell more higher-value products, making fights over raw steel and aluminum more about China’s past than the future.
docs.snippet: Beijing is pushing companies to sell more higher-value products, making fights over raw steel and aluminum more about China’s past than the future.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHENGKOUZHEN, China — Li Jinzi’s apartment lost its heat when the kilns went cold.

headline.main: Trump Condemns Chinese Factories. China Is Already Closing Some.

docs.abstract: Broad levies taking direct aim at the two countries would most likely affect other trading partners of the United States, illustrating the complexity of global commerce.
docs.snippet: Broad levies taking direct aim at the two countries would most likely affect other trading partners of the United States, illustrating the complexity of global commerce.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — When the Trump administration unveiled tariffs on imports of solar panels and washing machines — industries dominated by Chinese and South Korean businesses — they deliberately applied them to products from around the world.

headline.main: U.S. Tariffs, Aimed at China and South Korea, to Hit Targets Worldwide
headline.print_headline: A Global Ripple Effect in Import Levies

byline.original: By Keith Bradsher and Sui-Lee Wee

docs.abstract: As a stock market plunge that began in the United States spread globally, the wild swings underscored how the American economy retains defining influence across the globe.
docs.snippet: As a stock market plunge that began in the United States spread globally, the wild swings underscored how the American economy retains defining influence across the globe.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mere days ago, in what feels like a different era now, the biggest thing that people in control of money appeared to fear was complacency. Stock markets in the United States were surging, enthralled by the regulation-slashing, tax-shrinking predilections of President Trump. Every major economy in the world was expanding.

headline.main: The Era of Easy Money Is Ending, and the World Is Bracing for Shocks
headline.print_headline: World Is Bracing as Era  Of Easy Money Is Ending

docs.abstract: Jacob Zuma’s ouster as president is raising hopes of better fortunes for the nation’s moribund economy, but it will not happen easily.
docs.snippet: Jacob Zuma’s ouster as president is raising hopes of better fortunes for the nation’s moribund economy, but it will not happen easily.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the nearly quarter-century since apartheid ended in South Africa, the dominant African National Congress party has lost some of its moral authority as a vessel for lifting the fortunes of black people. To judge from furious street protests that have swept the nation, the party devolved in the eyes of many into a patronage network enriching a well-connected few.

headline.main: South Africa Sees Fresh Start for Economy, With the Same Challenges
headline.print_headline: South Africa’s Unemployment Rate Is 27%. Now, Perhaps, a Fresh Start.

docs.abstract: President Trump used two days in Davos to assuage the worst fears about his presidency among the global elite while aggressively courting investment.
docs.snippet: President Trump used two days in Davos to assuage the worst fears about his presidency among the global elite while aggressively courting investment.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — No one was declaring President Trump a changed man. Privately, executives and global leaders who had gathered in Davos continued to worry that the American president could yet indulge his worst instincts — and his penchant for shock on Twitter — to deliver a geopolitical crisis, open up a new front in trade hostilities or offend a vast group of people.

headline.main: Trump Arrived in Davos as a Party Wrecker. He Leaves Praised as a Pragmatist.
headline.print_headline: Trump Wins  Ample Praise As Pragmatist

byline.original: By Peter S. Goodman and Keith Bradsher

docs.abstract: The scandal at Punjab National Bank, a state-controlled lender, risks drying up the loans small and medium-size businesses need to power the country’s growth.
docs.snippet: The scandal at Punjab National Bank, a state-controlled lender, risks drying up the loans small and medium-size businesses need to power the country’s growth.
docs.lead_paragraph: NEW DELHI — One of India’s largest commercial lenders said on Wednesday that it had detected fraudulent transactions worth $1.77 billion at just one of its branches, raising concerns about the possible impact across the banking sector at a time when the country is struggling to meet its economic growth targets.

headline.main: $1.8 Billion in India Bank Fraud Raises Fears of Ripple Effects
headline.print_headline: Fears of Ripple Effect As India Confronts $1.8 Billion Bank Fraud
